First, we recognize that this problem involves multiplicative functions and Möbius inversion. By analyzing the given equation, we determine that \( f \) is multiplicative. This allows us to compute \( f \) on prime powers and then extend it to all integers using multiplicativity. We start by examining the case for prime powers. For a prime \( p \), setting \( n = p \) in the given equation, we find: \[ p \cdot f(1) = 1 \implies f(p) = 1 - p \] since \( f(1) = 1 \). Next, we verify that \( f(p^k) = 1 - p \) for any prime power \( p^k \). For example, for \( n = p^2 \), we compute: \[ f(p^2) + p \cdot f(p) + p^2 \cdot f(1) = 1 \implies f(p^2) + p(1 - p) + p^2 = 1 \implies f(p^2) = 1 - p \] Thus, for any prime power \( p^k \), \( f(p^k) = 1 - p \). Since \( f \) is multiplicative, for a number \( n \) with prime factorization \( n = p_1 p_2 \cdots p_r \), we have: \[ f(n) = \prod_{i=1}^r (1 - p_i) \] Applying this to \( 2023 = 7 \times 17^2 \), we get: \[ f(2023) = f(7 \times 17^2) = (1 - 7) \times (1 - 17) = (-6) \times (-16) = 96 \] Thus, the final answer is: \[ \boxed{96} \]
